sh (of Norman origin): habitational name from Villiers, the name of several places in France, all named from Late Latin <i>villare</i> ‘(part of an) outlying farm, dependent settlement’ (see   Villars  ). Compare   Devilliers  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Villars","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Henri.","French: habitational name from any of various places called Villars, from Late Latin <i>villare</i> ‘(part of an) outlying farm, dependent settlement’, a derivative of Latin <i>villa</i> ‘country house, estate’ (later used of a group of houses forming a settlement)."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>George</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"George","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Sir de Villiers was born in 1327, in Brooksby, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Geoffrey de Villiers, was 27 and his mother, Alice Brookesby  II x, was 23. He had at least 1 daughter. He died on 25 November 1416, in Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 89."},"et":{"1327–25 Nov 1416":"1327–25. november 1416","1323–1392":"1323–1392","1326–Male":"1326–Surnud","1327–1416":"1327–1416","1329–Male":"1329–Surnud","1368–1429":"1368–1429","1300–1356":"1300–1356","1304–1333":"1304–1333","25 Nov 1416":"25. november 1416","Aft 1333":"pärast 1333","1392":"1392","1327":"1327","1304":"1304","1326":"1326","1368":"1368","1356":"1356","1323":"1323","1333":"1333","1300":"1300","1429":"1429","1329":"1329","1416":"1416","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, , England":"Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Brooksby, Leicestershire, , England":"Brooksby, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kinoulton, Bingham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Kinoulton, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1327–25 Nov 1416":"1327–25. marraskuuta 1416","1323–1392":"1323–1392","1326–Male":"1326–Kuollut","1327–1416":"1327–1416","1329–Male":"1329–Kuollut","1368–1429":"1368–1429","1300–1356":"1300–1356","1304–1333":"1304–1333","25 Nov 1416":"25. marraskuuta 1416","Aft 1333":"1333 jälkeen","1392":"1392","1327":"1327","1304":"1304","1326":"1326","1368":"1368","1356":"1356","1323":"1323","1333":"1333","1300":"1300","1429":"1429","1329":"1329","1416":"1416","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, , England":"Melton Mowbray, Leicestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskun